	Jon, what if someone in the UK named their machine "EDU.ISI.UK"?
	Are reversed names confusing, especially since the European standard is
	to reverse the ordering of the name.

There is more to this than just a European convention.  There is considerable
momentum behind left-to-right names.  Phone companies, in particular,
tend to use left-to-right, and both AT&amp;T and the CCITT communities seem
to be as strongly a part of the left-to-right religion as they are a
part of the connection-oriented religion.

AT&amp;T is building steam toward proposing the syntax
	/usa/att/oh/mis/cbosgd!mark
for what you would think of as
	mark@cbosgd.mis.oh.att.usa

They use "usa" at the top level, being of the X.400 flavor.  The
first address above is intended as a shorthand for
	/c=usa/o=att/ou=oh/oh=mis/cn=cbosgd/!mark
(note the similarity to RFC 987).

The bang stuff is UNIX specific,
and intended to show how hosts are addressed; the real mailing
address would probably be
	/usa/att/oh/mis/mark.horton
which is short for
	/c=usa/o=att/ou=oh/ou=mis/cn=mark.horton/

The fact that the names look like UNIX filenames and similar to
Datakit addresses is no coincidence.  (In fact, since both sendmail
and mailx know how to mail to files if the name looks like a file,
this similarity may actually cause a problem.)

In any case, if ISO or CCITT ever adopted a right-to-left syntax,
I'd teleport myself to Mars (the teleporter being more likely to
be available than the CCITT right-to-left syntax.)  So far they
have been reluctant to specify ANY syntax, although they tend to
write things like
	Country		USA
	Organization	ATT
etc which show their thinking.

	Mark

